<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>February 5, 2003:  Few technologies ever enjoy the sort of rock-star celebrity that superconductors received in the late 1980s. <br>
<br>
Headlines the world over trumpeted the discovery of &quot;high temperature&quot; superconductors (abbreviated HTS), and the media and scientists alike gushed over the marvels that we could soon expect from this promising young technology. Levitating 300-mph trains, ultra-fast computers, and cheaper, cleaner electricity were to be just the beginning of its long and illustrious career.<br>
<br>
Today we might ask, like a Hollywood gossip columnist: what ever happened to the &quot;high-temp&quot; hype?<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
